comment:
When my parents got divorced my mom and her entire family talked so much shit about my dad to the judge, even talked about the crap he did before they had kids and my mother who had no job, no place of her own, and was going thru a psychotic episode got custody. My dad was a respiratory therapist who never missed work and lived in a super nice house up in the country with his gf at the time. I was so annoyed because I had been told I would be allowed to decide who I lived with since I was 16 and of legal age to do so and ya, never got that chance. I would have chosen my dad because he was strict and even though I hated it I knew I needed it, he had a job and was not going through a psychotic episode. While living with my mom after this, I began ditching school, ditched half my 10th-grade yr, and somehow passed. I did drugs, recreational, and otc. Got busted stealing twice too. And stole her car on numerous occasions and last and final time I did, ruined her transmission. In my defense of that, I did not yet actually have my license, nor did I know how to drive stick so my friend did the driving, still does not make it right ik. About a yr later my mom had a complete mental breakdown and handed custody over my dad. 


Having said all of that, I will note that it is likely my mother told the judge my dad was an alcoholic and smoked weed so maybe that was part of the judge's decision. I do not know, all I  do know is that despite these things, my dad went to work every single day and provided for his family and was sane. For my mom, on the other hand, this was not her first run-in with mental illness in my childhood.

comment:
I'm one of those men who has suffered due to a former spouse's unsubstantiated lies in a court of law. 
The time line:
- She lied to the police and prosecutor
- I was arrested and my daughter was taken from me
- I spent 6 months away from my child while fighting the false charges, I eventually proved she was a liar in criminal court with the help of the one honest friend she had
- I was then told by another court that it was too late to be awarded the very custody her lies had destroyed! To change arrangements then might damage my daughter's sense of well being and stability
What happened to her as a result of all this? Not a Damn Thing! NOTHING!

This took place 28 years ago, but there is a happy ending. My daughter is now 32, married and has given birth to three wonderful grandchildren and adopted a forth child. She is a fantastic mother! As a young teen, she escaped her mother's treacherous influence and came to live with me.  Her and I couldn't be closer to this very day! As for her mother, she wants nothing to do with her. And that has nothing to do with any influence I placed. One cannot be a selfish bitch and hide your true colors forever. So any man out there dealing with similar circumstances, Take Heart! Just be the best father you can be. The truth will always eventually come out. The best revenge is to live well and right.

comment:
Let's examine how false accusations play out typically.  The short answer is, women are believed, men aren't; women victims, men perpetrators.  It's no accident that MeToo, and feminism now and before it, has developed and maintains the narrative that only men are perpetrators, only women are victims, that women almost never lie about it, and an accusation is tantamount to insurmountable evidence of guilt towards the man.

It's such a common narrative that in virtually all discussions of the topic of domestic violence, it's the women who are victims of male abuse and women who are the ones who deserve all of the sympathy and support.  it's so ingrained in our society that there are no domestic violence shelters for men, no hotlines to call, no forms of counseling developed for the unique perspectives of men, and if there is ever a DV call it's always the men who are hauled away even if it's clear that the woman is the ravening unhinged mass of fury and the man is sitting there cowering and bloody while neighbors swear up and down she's the one beating on him.  This is called the Duluth Model and virtually all jurisdictions use it.  It was developed by feminists.

It's pervasive in family courts.  Women use it as an excuse all the time to get what they want, usually in the form of sole custody, no visitation for the kids, and possibly jail time.  There are countless men who are good loving fathers who have been victims of this, forcibly extricated from their kids' lives.  Imagine how painful that is for them?  It's no accident that women get custody of children in over 80% of cases.  False accusations are almost never investigated.

Many men lose careers, friends, family, their freedom, and sometimes their lives.  

Although recent studies by actual neutral third-party organizations like the CDC and BJS et al have shown that DV is at parity between men and women, that women instigate violence more often, that women are more likely to use weapons and deadly force, and that DV is usually reciprocal, men have no resources to escape it or deal with the consequences.  Most of the time when men admit that they are being abused, they aren't believed, by police, friends, or family.  Or they aren't taken seriously and that's the best case scenario.  They are turned away at shelters and usually the only resources a DV center might give a man suffering abuse is, get this: anger management training.  How insulting is that?  Most shelters won't allow a man on the premises.  There are no DV shelters for men.

No one takes it seriously.  Part of that is human nature - we're naturally more protective of women even at the expense of innocent men.  Most of it these days is a well-cultured decades-long protracted concerted campaign by feminists that, for some reason, have been allowed to completely dominate the narrative on all things gendered.

That we get the odd case like this is a fluke.  Looking at other high profile cases of proven false accusation like UVa, Duke lacrosse, and Jian Ghomeshi, nothing happens to the accusers even when the intent was proven to be completely malicious.  In most cases, even after exoneration many people still believe the accused are guilty and most of them are never able to get their lives back fully.

comment:
I believe that it is critical that this story be tracked closely by men's rights groups. You KNOW that if Depp had done even a fraction of what she did he would have been jailed, period, end of story. But we have a very clear case here of the shoe being on the other foot. (Question: Is it three years for doing all those things, or does the law allow for three years for each instance?) As this drama plays out, it needs to be kept in the public view so people know about it and the TRUE facts of the case. Then we can pick up A.H and swing her like a club at misandric actors:
